<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Ministry of Justice</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10.5pt; line-height:85%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:85%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.9pt">Written evidence from</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.9pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.9pt"> Ministry of Justice</span></p><p style="font-size:10.5pt; line-height:85%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.9pt">              </span></p><p style="font-size:10.5pt; line-height:85%; margin:16.2pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">TRANSFORMING REHABILITATION: INFORMATION SESSION</span></p><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">I understand that, following our recent conversation, the Justice Committee Clerk has now been in touch with the Department to arrange an informal information session </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">with the senior officials who are leading the Transforming Rehabilitation work. I am </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">pleased that you and your colleagues are able to take up this offer to find out more about our important plans for reducing reoffe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">nding through this </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt"> of r</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">eforms.</span></p><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">As you are aware, the Transforming Rehabilitation Strategy published in May this year set out our plans for transforming the way in which offenders are managed in the community in order to bring down reoffending rates. The key elements of the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt"> are:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt; margin:16.2pt 43.2pt 0pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">creating a new National Probation Service that will be responsible for protecting the public from the most dangerous offenders, and 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies who will focus on low</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt"> and medium risk offenders;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt; margin:16.2pt 43.2pt 0pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">opening up the market to a diverse range of new rehabilitation providers while introducing a new payment mechanism to focus them relentlessly on driving down reoffending rates;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt; margin:16.2pt 43.2pt 0pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">extending statutory rehabilitation to those offenders who serve short sentences, and who currently receive no statutory support despite having the highest reoffending rates; and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt; margin:16.2pt 43.2pt 0pt 32pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">reorganising</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt"> the prison estate to put in place an unprecedented nationwide through the prison gate resettlement service meaning that for the first time most offenders will be given continuous support from custody into the community</span></li></ol><p style="margin:1.8pt 43.2pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">Funding for the supervision of offenders makes up a sizeable proportion of the Department's budget, and we are faced with the challenge of trying to do better for less. We can either impose further cuts on the structures we have, risking increases in re-offending and leaving short-sentenced offenders without support after release. Or we can reform the system so that it provides more effective rehabilitation at a better value to the taxpayer, in a way that is sustainable for the future — and reinvest</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">some of the savings in support for short sentence prisoners, an objective that has wide support. We can only do that if we bring in the best of the public, voluntary and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">private sectors to work with offenders: it is the reforms in their totality that will bring </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">us closer to the important goal of a year-on-year, incremental reduction in re-offending rates.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">Before you meet with officials in the Department I thought it would be helpful to set </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">out the progress we are making carefully, and systematically, to transfer from the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">current system to the new operating model in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Autumn</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> 2014. I have set out below </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">some of the key activities that will be taking place over the course of the next year </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">around each key part of the reforms — this includes the work that is being undertaken </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">around people transition, testing the system, and the Transforming Rehabilitation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.2pt">competition.</span></p><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.75pt">1 - Creating the National Probation Service and Community Rehabilitation </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.85pt">Companies: Transition of Probation Service</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Programme</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> has been engaging closely with the leadership of Probation Trusts, including Human Resources leads, on the support that they need to transition staff to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">the new system. The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">Programme</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt"> has established a People Transition Service (PTS) </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">to support this work and the PTS have had regular contact — both face-to-face and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">through teleconferences - with Trusts about how the plans for moving people to the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">new system are progressing.</span></p><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">We are committed to giving Trusts all the information, resources and support they </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">need to successfully transition to the new system. In November the staff allocation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">process will be commenced in all Trusts and we will work with Trusts in the coming </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.55pt">months to clarify any issues relating to the allocation of both people and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.6pt">infrastructure to either the National Probation Service or the Community </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">Rehabilitation Companies.</span></p><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Programme</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> has worked with operational staff from Trusts to test the design of the future operating model. This has included testing the developing risk allocation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">tool, the case allocation process and the Payment mechanism. We will ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.2pt">offenders are clear who their Offender Manager will be by having a considered </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">process for transferring cases. The Department remains committed to continuing to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">work closely with Trusts to test key aspects of the new system. We have plans in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">place to roll out business readiness tests at key stages of implementation so that we </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.35pt">can ensure we are managing the transition to the new system in a safe and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">measured way.</span></p><p style="margin:21.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.2pt">This testing will support our plans for operational delivery to transfer from the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Probation Trusts to the National Probation Service and Community Rehabilitation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.2pt">Companies by April 2014. At this point all critical systems and process will be in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">place, so that in the run up to the Autumn we can focus on ensuring that, at the end </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">of the competition, providers will take on viable going concerns. We want there to be </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">continuity in the staff who are managing the caseload, continuity in the buildings that are being used and fully functioning ICT systems, which is why our focus during this </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">period will be on ensuring stability as the changes bed in.</span></p><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.15pt">The creation of the new National Probation Service and Community Rehabilitation</span><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">Companies by April next year is the first phase in a transition that will then continue</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.45pt">with the award of contracts to providers later next year. We expect to see </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">transformation taking place gradually, as providers then start to re-design services by </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">taking advantage of the new freedom to innovate and bringing together expertise </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">from a wider range of providers. This phased approach to implementation means that we can move to the new system in a safe and measured way.</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">2 - Opening up the Market to a diverse range of new rehabilitation providers </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.2pt">and introducing Payment by Results</span></p><p style="margin:16.2pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.15pt">The competition process is now underway, following the publication of the OJEU </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">notice in September.</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">We know from our market engagement events that there is a high level of interest in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">the competition for offender services from a diverse range of providers across the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">voluntary, community and private sectors. As of mid-October over 100 </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> have expressed their interest in competing as potential Tier </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.4pt">I </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">providers, and of that number 70 have completed the registration process via our e-sourcing portal. It has </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">always been our intention for these reforms to open up the market to a variety of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">providers. Bringing together the best of the public, private and voluntary sectors will allow us to draw on a broader range of expertise, with payment by results offering a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">strong incentive to improve upon existing service delivery. For our system really to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">work, I want, to see a whole range of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> working to get to grips with </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.4pt">offenders' life management problems, signposting them to accommodation, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.15pt">education, or health services, or offering a mentor. The competition process has </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">been designed to enable bids from a range of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">, including the voluntary </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.2pt">and social sector, and to enable genuine partnerships to be formed in order to tackle </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">reoffending. To support this, the Department is embedding good market stewardship </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">principles into the system so that there is fair, reasonable and transparent treatment </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">of all those involved in the direct and indirect provision of services.</span></p><p style="margin:27pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Due to the high level of interest and the subsequent number of clarification questions </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">asked by providers in preparing their responses, we have allowed potential providers </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">an additional 14 calendar days for their pre-qualification responses to be </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">finalised</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">, which must now be submitted by 14 November. The competition timetable remains on track, and the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Programme's</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> competition team and transition team are working </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">closely together to ensure both </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">workstreams</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> are aligned.</span></p><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.35pt">3 - Extending Statutory Rehabilitation</span></p><p style="margin:16.2pt 0pt 5pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The Offender Rehabilitation Bill, which is passing through Parliament and today had </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">its second reading in the House, extends statutory supervision for those offenders </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.35pt">who receive custodial sentences of less than 12 months. The Bill will enable </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">rehabilitation services to be extended to this group of offenders for the first time, and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">to start to address the high reoffending rates we currently see. It demonstrates to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">them that the Government is serious about giving them the support they need to turn </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">their backs on crime, while at the same time being clear there will be consequences if </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">offenders choose to keep on offending.</span></p><p style="margin:16.2pt 0pt 5pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.25pt">4 - Establishing the Through the Gate Resettlement Service</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">We recently announced that 82 prisons will be designated as 'resettlement prisons' </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">so that providers can continue the rehabilitation work they have begun in custody into </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">the community. Work is currently being undertaken by the Department to test the model in the North West. This testing will inform the planning for </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">reorgnising</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">remainder of the estate in the New Year.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:88%; margin:16.2pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">Assurance</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.15pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.15pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.15pt"> team has been working closely with the Probation Association, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.35pt">Probation Chiefs Association, and with Probation Trusts at each stage of the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.2pt">process, and we will continue to do so as we implement the reforms. We have </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">established a Sounding Board, which has been meeting since March, so that we can hear directly from Trust leadership.</span></p><p style="margin:16.2pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.15pt">We have developed a Business and System Readiness process for the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.15pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.15pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.3pt">to provide assurance that the restructured business, its systems and support </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">infrastructure, including shared services, are ready to go live.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">This process aims to:</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.4pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.4pt">Ensure that every aspect of the new service and the system reform being</span><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">developed are thoroughly validated prior to proceeding with implementation;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.4pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">Provide the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt"> and the business with the assurance that the system </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">performs as expected in an environment that mimics implementation as closely </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">as possible;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.4pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">Support the 'business as usual' function to ensure that structures and resources </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">are in place to respond to the reforms as required</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.15pt">The team are currently working with colleagues from Probation Trusts, MoJ and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">NOMS and other stakeholders to define the criteria that will be used to test readiness </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">at each stage of transition. The team have developed these criteria with input from </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">the Ministerial Sounding Board as well as discussions with a number of Probation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Trusts and practitioner groups.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">There is no doubt that this is a significant </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt"> of reforms, but one that we are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">implementing carefully, with the transition taking place in a series of phases. It is my </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">view that we cannot afford to not act now while reoffending rates remain so high. It is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">also my view that to delay these reforms would create more uncertainty for staff </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">within Probation Trusts about their future role in the system, uncertainty that I would </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.2pt">like to avoid.</span></p><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 5.4pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">I hope that this information will be useful to you and your Committee colleagues in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">preparing for the areas you wish to focus on during the information session with </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">officials from the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Programme</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> and I look forward to hearing the detail of the areas that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt">you discuss.</span></p><p style="font-size:10.5pt; line-height:88%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10.5pt; line-height:88%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">November 2013</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>